<TEXT>
the deputy defense minister denied 
monday that hungary was involved in selling advanced soviet 
military technology to the united states as alleged in a published 
report 
the state mti news agency said the newspaper mai nap quoted 
brig gen ferenc szombathelyi as saying in an interview published 
monday as far as hungary is concerned i am positive that the 
hungarian military authorities did nothing which could have 
endangered our national integrity 
defense ministry spokesman col gyoergy keleti told mti that 
soviet military technological means and secrets could not have 
been supplied from hungary 
he said hungary never had the most modern soviet military 
equipment that the standard of military technology here lagged 
behind the most uptodate soviet technology by up to 10 years mti 
reported 
the washington post quoting unidentified intelligence 
sources in washington and abroad said in sundays editions that 
the united states secretly bought advanced soviet military 
technology from romania for 10 years prior to the december 
revolution that ousted dictator nicolae ceausescu 
ceausescu was executed on christmas day 
the newspaper said the romanian connection was part of a larger 
weaponsbuying operation that allowed the us military to obtain 
important components of soviet air defense systems 
it quoted its sources as saying the united states paid more than 
250 million the past 10 years to obtain the latest versions of 
sovietmade weapons systems through contacts in other east bloc 
countries including hungary 
asked if he considered the washington post article a mere 
slander szombathelyi was quoted as replying as far as hungary 
is concerned it definitely is 
but he was quoted as adding that a thorough inquiry would be 
launched into the matter and that a parliamentary inquiry was also 
expected 
mai nap said szombathelyi responded when asked how moscow 
counterintelligence could have been unaware of the reportedly 
extensive operation that is exactly why i consider these 
allegations pure nonsense 
he was said to have added however that that everything is 
possible in trade 
the washington post report said the democratization of eastern 
europe had disrupted the broader operation but not stopped it 
</TEXT>
