<TEXT>
unlike other western countries the united 
states will not be represented on the ministerial level at a 
conference on the environment that opens this week in bergen the 
national news agency ntb reported 
the action for a common future conference in the west coast 
city is expected to be attended by between 40 and 50 cabinet 
ministers among a total of 600 delegates from 34 countries it 
begins tuesday and runs to may 16 
the american delegation will be headed by john a knauss a 
commerce department official and former professor of oceanography 
the agency quoted press attache john matel of the us embassy as 
saying 
ntb said in the report sunday that knauss would be heading a 
delegation of 12 politicians and lowlevel civil servants 
representing the departments of state and energy and the 
environment protection agency 
the norwegian government expressed regret that the united states 
was not being represented by a cabinet minister the agency said 
it quoted norways state secretary kai eide as saying it had 
hoped epa chief william k reilly would have taken part 
the bergen conference aims to follow up recommendations of the 
our common future report by the un world commission on 
environment and development 
it was organized by norway in cooperation with the european 
commission for europe which includes the united states and canada 
</TEXT>
