<TEXT>
life is a slow tedious limbo at a place called 
krome and tempers are short and getting shorter 
krome the krome service processing center is where newcomers 
from haiti and other countries await word on their future in the 
united states 
many people pass through the fencedin holding center but most 
are haitian refugees some with stories to tell of alleged abuse 
and neglect at the hands of the us immigration and naturalization 
service 
miamis haitian community is generally considered peaceful but 
on april 29 more than 1000 haitians demonstrated outside krome 
tearing at its fences after years of seeing their countrymen locked 
up while others go free 
we want freedom and justice for the haitian refugees and all 
the refugees detained said the rev gerard jeanjuste a haitian 
community leader we must break down the walls of krome which 
reminds us of hitlerism 
on average twothirds of the centers 400 or so residents are 
haitians they are picked up at the airport with fake passports and 
visas or plucked from rickety boats by the coast guard while trying 
to slip into the united states 
arrivals at krome a former missile base on the steamy edge of 
the everglades 25 miles west of miami are dressed in orange 
uniforms and given medical exams and then they wait 
the most horrible part of this place is time said nuhu 
aminu 35 a tv production specialist from nigeria 
the average stay at krome is 18 months sometimes more than two 
years detainees wait to learn whether they will be deported or 
released 
the one thing people kind of lose sight of is that we dont go 
out and try to shanghai these people krome administrator 
constance weiss said theyre here because they attempted to 
break the law 
in affidavits many signed with encoded names to avoid 
reprisals krome detainees have told of experiences far more 
horrible than agonized waiting women have said they are sexually 
abused and harassed by guards 
the krome officers often told the male detainees at krome that 
they had sex with the female detainees they bragged about this and 
laughed and thought it was real great said chantale pierre a 
former detainee who now lives in miami 
men and women have complained of beatings and restricted access 
to telephones and bathrooms haitian detainees say latins get 
preferential treatment 
detainees say they often arent given enough time to eat their 
meals and have charged that an aspirin substitute is given for any 
complaint 
on many occasions we are physically abused one detainee 
said since we are scared and dont speak english we keep 
quiet 
the allegations angered many in the haitian community sparking 
the april 29 demonstration that ended with no arrests and the 
retreat of the protesters 
the allegations have stirred up ins officials two of whom 
visited krome on april 24 shortly afterward the agency announced 
the additions of two more immigration judges and 27 guards to 
improve conditions and speed up the wait 
on may 1 the ins began an alreadyplanned test program under 
which about 200 detainees will be released in miami los angeles 
new york and san francisco they must meet certain conditions 
including having what appears to be a good case for asylum and a 
source of income or support posting a bond of 500 to 2500 and 
agreeing in writing to surrender for deportation if ordered 
the justice department is looking into allegations of abuse at 
krome because of the investigation miami ins director richard 
smith and krome officials would not comment on the detainees 
complaints 
meanwhile life at krome drags on 
detainees spend their days cleaning their quarters watching 
television playing volleyball or basketball outside or lounging 
under shelters men and women cluster at the 10foot fences that 
keep them apart 
sometimes we stay in bed think about everything said a 
haitian who asked that her name not be revealed think about your 
country think about your family we suffer 
detainees also take classes they can work toward high school 
equivalency diplomas learn english or study crafts such as 
ceramics and sewing some work earning a dollar a day as laborers 
at the camp 
sick detainees go to a clinic with an emergency room and xray 
and dental facilities mental health professionals also are on duty 
detainess watch video movies mostly in english every night 
weiss said 
one thing you have to do is keep yourself together said 
detto bilkerdyk who works in the krome sign shop a former 
military policeman from suriname he said he left home fearing for 
his life after refusing orders to commit executions 
if they deport me back home i know im dead he said 
