<TEXT>
andrei sakharov the late soviet physicist and 
human rights champion wrote that his life and work in many ways 
paralleled the violence repression and eventually the reforms that 
have swept his homeland 
excerpts from sakharovs memoirs appeared in the sunday times of 
london in advance of british publication in july 
he died in moscow on dec 14 at age 68 after a heart attack 
the book titled memoirs will be published in june in the 
united states by alfred a knopf inc excerpts also will appear in 
time magazines may 14 and may 21 issues 
sakharov who endured years of persecution by soviet authorities 
but was mourned as a hero and visionary recalled the awe and fear 
he felt when he heard of the atomic bombing of hiroshima by the 
united states in 1945 
i was so stunned that my legs practically gave way wrote 
sakharov who was considered the father of his own countrys 
hydrogen bomb 
there could be no doubt that my fate and the fate of many 
others perhaps of the entire world had changed overnight he 
said in the sunday times excerpts something new and awesome had 
entered our lives a product of the greatest of the sciences of 
the discipline i revered 
in the time excerpts he wrote of the tragedy cruelty and 
terror of the era of his childhood the 1920s and early 1930s 
and remembered the stalinist repression that left parents afraid to 
speak freely before their children 
this reluctance to reveal ones thoughts even to ones own son 
may be the most haunting sign of those times he wrote 
later sakharovs calls for political reforms presaged many of 
the changes under soviet president mikhail s gorbachev who 
allowed sakharov to return to moscow in 1986 after nearly seven 
years of internal exile in the city of gorky 
in the memoirs sakharov said that after world war ii when he 
was made a member of igor tamms topsecret team developing the 
hbomb at the physics institute of the soviet academy of sciences 
nobody asked if i wanted to take part i had no real choice 
but the concentration total absorption and energy that i 
brought to the task were my own he recalled in the sunday times 
exceprts 
i understood the terrifying inhuman nature of the weapons we 
were building he wrote but the recent war had also been an 
exercise in barbarity 
it was sakharovs call for a worldwide nuclear test ban in the 
late 1950s that first brought him into conflict with soviet 
authorities 
during the last three decades of his life he fought against the 
jailing of innocent people for free emigration and for disarmament 
and other causes 
he said he was not convinced that mutual assured nuclear 
destruction had truly helped to keep the peace 
thermonuclear weapons could end human civilization they have 
become so frightening that the very thought of using them seems 
unreal their credibility as a deterrent has thus decreased while 
their threat has increased enormously he wrote 
the first extract from sakharovs memoirs dealt mainly with his 
being sent to internal exile in 1980 for criticizing soviet 
intervention in afghanistan 
