<TEXT>
political passions have come alive in 
romania after decades of repression and their target is often 
interim president ion iliesco seen by critics as a communist agent 
in liberal disguise 
a roundtheclock rally by iliescus foes which began sixteen 
days ago has transformed downtown university square into what the 
demonstrators call a communistfree zone 
iliescu was a high official under dictator nicolae ceausescu 
who was overthrown and executed in december but fell out of favor 
and was given relatively unimportant party jobs he gained 
prominence during the revolution when the national salvation front 
was formed to run the government 
up to 10000 people have filled the square to applaud speakers 
from national figures to workers who demand that iliescu resign 
about 40 tents have been pitched around the square and 57 
protesters are on a hunger strike 
supporters of iliescu have held at least one rally and rumors 
persist of plans for an attack on the university square protest 
knots of people form around university square every day to argue 
about iliescu and the elections scheduled for may 20 which will be 
the first free vote for romanians in 50 years 
people here in the square hate iliescu because he wants us to 
live in darkness a woman shouted thrusting her chin toward a 
supporter of the president who retorted he doesnt want to keep 
romania in darkness he wants to create a bright romania 
another woman swept an arm toward the crowd in the square and 
asked how can romania become a prosperous country if people 
camp outside like this without working 
on april 29 tens of thousands of people demonstrated against 
iliescu in timisoara dej and the port city of constanta 
timisoara in western romania was where the uprising against 
ceausecu began 
in rural romania horse carts still are the principal mode of 
transport and people wait up to a week for telephone calls to or 
from abroad many have no access to television cannot read 
newspapers and accept rumors as fact 
is it true that revolution has broken out in the capital 
asked a gypsy woman openly selling black market cigarettes in 
tecuci a moldavian town 150 miles northeast of bucharest 
moldavia has been relatively quiet but there is a surge of 
nationalism among moldavians across the soviet border which was 
opened for six hours of visafree travel on sunday 
