<TEXT>
thousands of people who came to 
industrialized southern brazil seeking work are now returning home 
frustrated by the rising unemployment the governments austerity 
plan has wrought 
i arrived here with almost nothing and im going back with 
less said jose loreno filho 30 as he prepared to board a bus 
late last week at sao paulos huge tiete bus station 
he had a ticket home to a tiny village in impoverished alagoas 
state on the northeastern coast 
loreno filho who had once worked a small plot of land in 
alagoas scrimped together about 50 and bus fare to come to sao 
paulo in early march he stayed with relatives and hoped to earn 
money to bring his wife and four children to join him 
but on march 16 brazils new president fernando collor de 
mello launched his austerity plan in a bid to defeat record 
inflation that reached nearly 5000 percent over the past year 
while the initiatives which include an 18month freeze on 115 
billion in bank deposits have drastically reduced the cost of 
living businesses have fired hundreds of thousands of workers 
i walked the streets for the past two months and there arent 
any jobs said loreno filho the streets arent paved with gold 
the way i imagined 
sao paulo brazils industrial and financial center has 
attracted millions of migrants during the past two decades most 
came from the northeast to escape that regions grinding poverty 
but since collors economic plan was announced the stream of 
economic refugees has been at least temporarily reversed 
our buses to the northeast have been packed for the past six 
weeks and when buses from the region arrive at the station 
