<TEXT>
a close observer may doubt congress sincerity 
on issues such as the environment abortion and the deficit but 
not on campaign finance reform 
many lawmakers sincerely want to reform their campaign opponents 
out of contention 
for the past two years the idea of revamping the federal 
campaign finance system has been at the top of the congressional 
agenda 
but so far theres been more heat than light from the 535 
experts grappling with the issue from their seats in the capitol 
the senate deadlocked repeatedly on the issue in 1988 and 
agreement remains elusive today house republican and democratic 
leaders formed a task force on campaign reform in the wake of the 
ethicsrelated resignation of former speaker jim wright and nearly 
a year later it is stalled 
theres little disagreement over the problem campaigns cost so 
much that raising money for them is a fulltime job prone to 
conflicts of interest and not leaving much time for legislating 
but almost any solution favors one side over another 
the main democratic proposal would cap the total amount that 
candidates may spend in a campaign republicans dont like the idea 
because the democrats get a lot of offthebooks help primarily 
from labor unions 
the gop would eliminate most donations from political action 
committees nonmonetary help from labor and other groups and give 
the political parties a bigger role in house and senate elections 
pacs give mightily to democratic incumbents while the republican 
party with president bush as chief fundraiser can easily outspend 
the democratic party 
some democrats favor public financing of campaigns perhaps 
through an income tax checkoff but that proposal is anathema to 
most conservatives 
the differences between the parties are so sharp that in the 
house speaker thomas foley dwash and minority leader robert 
michel rill recently agreed to hold off action until later in 
the spring in hopes the senate can find some common ground 
it is widely expected that the houses majority democrats will 
muscle their bill past republican objections but the gop members 
will get a chance to vote on their alternative that way both 
sides can go home to the voters and say they supported reform 
the senate could do the same thing but probably not as tidily 
and with more acrimony if pushed hard enough perhaps by the 
continuing scandal over campaign donations from executives from 
failed savings and loans its possible a bill could emerge 
there are a few areas of possible agreement for example 
mandated discounts for television campaign advertising 
but even proposals that would hit incumbent candidates from both 
parties equally can be sensitive such as the proposal by senate 
republicans to place tough restrictions on taxpayerfinanced 
mailings by senators in an election year 
the congressional frank is one of the big advantages 
incumbents have over their challengers the minority republicans 
are looking to make all of congress more vulnerable to increase 
their own chances of taking over 
but house speaker foley recently refused to consider even the 
moderate step of disclosing publicly how much each house member 
spends on mass mailings foley said the public has repeatedly said 
in polls that it wants to hear from elected officials more often 
not less 
its too early to rule out a significant revamping of campaign 
laws but resistance to any proposed changes must be expected 
because those 535 experts on capitol hill have proven they can 
master the current system 
despite grumbling about its burdens its still the devil they 
know 
