<TEXT>
nearly a week of sitins and hunger strikes in 
mongolia ended after the countrys largest opposition group agreed 
to a compromise and joined a government advisory body mongolian 
radio said today 
the mongolian democratic association decided late sunday to join 
other opposition groups in accepting a government offer to set up 
an advisory council from which they can submit draft bills and 
suggestions to the communistdominated legislature 
shortly after the agreement was reached the mda and its 
supporters ended hunger strikes in three cities and sitins in the 
mongolian capital of ulan bator and several other cities mongolian 
radio said 
mongolian president punsalmaagiin ochirbat meanwhile flew home 
from china two days earlier than planned but neither the chinese 
nor the mongolian embassy gave any explanation 
he had arrived friday for a sixday visit that normalized 
relations after nearly three decades of coolness caused by the 
chinesesoviet split mongolia is a soviet satellite 
after his departure the official chinese news agency xinhua 
released the text of a chinesemongolian communique that said the 
visit opened up a bright prospect for further expanding and 
developing bilateral relations 
it said ochirbat invited chinese president yang shangkun and 
premier li peng to visit ulan bator and they accepted no dates 
were set 
the communique also said the two sides believed it was useful 
to exchange information and experience on socialist construction 
and economic reform and were ready to hold more meetings on the 
subject 
mongolia has been following the soviet example of allowing 
vigorous political debate but moving slowly on economic reform 
while china has introduced wideranging economic reforms without 
relaxing political controls 
china has shown concern about moves toward democracy in mongolia 
by curbing travel there by its citizens and increasing surveillance 
over ethnic mongols in china chinas communist party leader jiang 
zemin advised ochirbat on saturday that internal stability is 
essential for economic development 
the wave of sitins and hunger strikes in mongolia began last 
week to press for the resignation of the legislature dominated by 
the ruling communist party and establishment of a multiparty 
provisional legislature until elections are held this summer 
a source in ulan bator interviewed by telephone said the 
sitin by 25 to 30 people in the capitals central square which 
began wednesday had ended by midnight sunday 
it never attracted crowds of more than several hundred said the 
source who spoke on condition of anonymity 
in contrast thousands of people attended rallies in january and 
february at which the mda and other opposition groups pressed their 
initial demands for democratic reform many of those demands were 
met including that the communists give up their constitutional 
guarantee of power and allow opposition parties 
local newspapers reported today that the opposition groups had 
agreed to work together to restructure mongolias political system 
the source said 
details of the advisory councils size function and makeup were 
not disclosed but it is to work under the legislatures council of 
ministers and be allowed to draft legislation the source said 
the president proposed the council as an alternative to 
opposition demands that the 370member legislature resign and a 
multiparty legislature be set up until summer elections more than 
93 percent of the lawmakers are members of the communist party 
</TEXT>
