<TEXT>
the bush administration announced today it 
will restrict the import of archaeological treasures from the sipan 
region of peru 
the action is designed to help curb looting in the sipan 
region and responds to a request from peru for help presidential 
spokesman marlin fitzwater said in a statement 
the action means artifacts from sipan entering the united states 
without an export permit from the peruvian government will be 
seized by us customs agents and returned the statement said 
the united states believes that the illegal trade in cultural 
property does immense damage to our hemispheric cultural 
heritage the white house statement said 
the south american nation asked for assistance in deterring 
looting at sipan site of what archaeologists call the richest 
precolumbian tomb found intact in the western hemisphere 
the tomb was discovered at sipan in 1987 experts have said it 
has yielded important new information about the moche civilization 
that inhabited the river valleys of northern peru from ad 100 to 
700 intricately crafted gold gilded copper and silver artifacts 
reportedly have been discovered at the site 
the united states believes that the illegal trade in cultural 
property does immense damage to our hemispheric cultural heritage 
and is willing to cooperate with other governments of this region 
and elsewhere to prevent illegal trafficking in archaeological 
treasures the white house statement said 
the united states imposed emergency restrictions on some 
precolumbian artifacts from el salvador in 1987 and on some 
andean textiles from bolivia last year similar requests from the 
governments of canada and guatemala are pending 
</TEXT>
