syria announced today it will not attend 
an emergency arab summit in baghdad capital of its archrival 
iraq arab officials said 
the syrians instead proposed that foreign ministers of the 
22member arab league meet in tunis to recommend an alternative 
venue the syrians have said they werent consulted before the 
meeting place was selected 
it was not immediately clear whether the summit would go ahead 
the syrian decision stymied arab efforts led by saudi arabia 
egypt and jordan to mediate a reconciliation between syrian 
president hafez assad and iraqi president saddam hussein and end an 
11yearold rift 
foreign minister farouk alsharaa conveyed syrias decision 
today to arab league secretarygeneral chadlie klibi who arrived 
in damascus late sunday arab officials said on condition of 
anonymity 
the official syrian arab news agency reported the meeting 
between sharaa and klibi 
sharaa suggested the arab league council convene to conduct 
consultations on a convenient venue and date for the summit and to 
agree on the topics to be discussed at the forum the news agency 
said 
the arab league council comprises the foreign ministers of the 
21 member states plus the palestine liberation organiztaions 
political department chief regarded as a foreign minister in the 
arab world 
earlier saudi arabia syrias main bankroller threw its weight 
behind an emergency arab summit in baghdad saudi arabia was 
understood to have said previously that it would not attend a 
summit in baghdad unless syria did 
