<TEXT>
the united states is barring the import of 
looted peruvian archaeologial treasures to protect them from greedy 
art dealers and collectors the administration said monday 
the import ban is the strongest action possible to assist peru 
in preserving its cultural heritage bruce s gelb director of 
the us information agency said at a news conference 
the ban affects artifacts being stolen by armed looters from the 
sipan region of peru the site of rich intact precolombian tombs 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said in a statement 
cesar atala the peruvian ambassador to the united states said 
the ban will help us avoid the enormous lure of the us market 
the presidents cultural property advisory commission found that 
the us market for objects looted from the tombs is so large it 
is encouraging looting in the region gelb said 
intricately crafted gold gilded copper and silver artifacts 
have been discovered at the site 
michael h lane deputy commissioner of us customs compared 
the looting to drug smuggling 
we see the same techniques and the same motive greed as we 
see every day in the smuggling of narcotics lane said 
under the presidential order requested by peru artifacts from 
the region will be seized by customs agents and returned to peru 
unless the items are accompanied by an export permit issued by the 
peruvian government 
atala said the looting was preventing archaeologists from 
evaluating the material in its original sites and from studying the 
moche culture its origins and its relationship to other 
precolombian cultures 
experts have said the tombs discovered in 1987 have yielded 
important information about the civilization that inhabited the 
river valleys of northern peru from 100 to 700 ad 
lane said the ban would not be retroactive but that objects 
from the region already in the united states would be affected if 
the artifacts are proved to have been stolen 
the united states imposed emergency restrictions on monumental 
precolombian artifacts from el salvador in 1987 and on some andean 
textiles from bolivia last year similar requests from canada and 
guatemala are pending 
</TEXT>
