chrysler corp is recalling eight models of 
1985 plymouths and dodges that have flunked federal exhaust 
emission standards the environmental protection agency announced 
monday 
the recall to replace part of the carburetor choke system 
affects 383700 vehicles the plymouth horizon turismo reliant 
and reliant wagon and the dodge omni charger aries and aries 
wagons the epa said 
chrysler agreed to the recall after the cars all with 22liter 
engines exceeded the allowed hydrocarbon and carbon monoxide 
exhaust emission levels in routine epa tests the agency said 
the recall does not affect cars sold in california 
the manufacturer will replace the choke vacuum delay valve 
which allows a richer mixture of fuel and air when the engine is 
started cold chrysler has designed an improved valve the epa 
said the work is to be done free by chryslerplymouth or dodge 
dealers 
hydrocarbons when combined with sunlight and other pollutants 
contribute to the formation of smog the epa says that excessive 
carbon monoxide levels in the atmosphere impair heart functions and 
are harmful to people with lung disease anemia and peripheral 
vascular disease 
