the benefits of incumbency particularly in receiving donations 
from political action committees 
incumbents had a more than 6to1 overall fundraising edge over 
challengers and a 16to1 edge when it came to pac donations 
according to the fec data 
overall the fec computer analysis showed receipts by 1990 
congressional campaigns totaled 1925 million from jan 1 1989 
through the end of march 7 percent more than was raised in the 
comparable period in the 198788 election cycle 
of those receipts 150 million went to incumbents and 
incumbents accounted for the 946 million of the reported 127 
million in spending 
the 127 million spent by 1269 candidates for house and senate 
seats up this year represents a 12 percent increase over the 
198788 cycle at this point two years ago 1344 candidates had 
spent 113 million 
the analysis was based on the quarterly finance reports all 
campaigns were required to file last month the reports detail 
campaign activity through march 31 and include all candidates who 
raised and spent money on 1990 congressional races even if they 
since have dropped out 
for many candidates the campaign season and its accompanying 
fundraising is just kicking into high gear but the fecs 
computer analysis showed the campaigns had a combined 1385 
million on hand at the end of march 
the clear leader in cash on hand was sen phil gramm rtexas 
who reported having 65 million as of march 31 the house 
candidate with the most on hand was california democratic rep mel 
levine with 15 million seventy candidates most of them 
longshots in house races reported zero balances 
the biggest spender so far on a 1990 senate race was new jersey 
democrat bill bradley who reported spending 36 million so far on 
his reelection effort leading spending for 1990 house races was 
california republican rep robert dornan who reported spending 
968525 as of march 31 
other highlights 
the 1151 candidates in 1990 house elections raised 1092 
million and spent 797 million in the january 1989march 1990 
period those candidates raised 524 million in individual 
contributions and 419 million from pacs 
the 118 senate candidates raised 83 million and spent 47 
million in the 15month period with 562 million of the receipts 
coming from individuals and 196 million from pacs 
the 444 incumbents seeking reelection reported total campaign 
receipts of 150 million in the 15month period dwarfing the 234 
million raised by 600 challengers another 19 million was raised 
by the 225 candidates in races in which there is no incumbent 
of 61 million in pac donations to 1990 candidates during the 
15 months 545 million went to incumbents 33 million to 
challengers and 35 million to candidates for open seats the 
latter group includes house members seeking open senate seats 
 
