said and he thinks the delegation will be received 
a similar effort by lithuania which declared independence march 
11 proved fruitless 
the soviet president imposed an oil and natural gas embargo on 
lithuania idling 12500 workers he refuses to negotiate with 
lithuania until the republic of 38 million people rescinds several 
laws passed after independence was declared 
lithuania also must return to the soviet unions constitutional 
framework gorbachev says 
the three baltic republics of lithuania latvia and estonia were 
forcibly absorbed into the soviet union in 1940 soon after 
gorbachev began his reforms all three initiated independence 
drives he offered them more say in economic and political 
decisions but said secession would have to be by soviet law 
of latvias 26 million residents just over half are ethnic 
latvians and a third are ethnic russians many of the nonlatvians 
especially russians oppose secession 
latvia unlike lithuania did not suspend its soviet 
constitution upon declaring independence it just added sections 
calling for independence and democracy 
estonia last month declared it intends to restore its 
independence and called the soviet union an occupying power but 
it set no date for the split and left the door open for 
negotiations gorbachev threatened estonia but took no action 
against it 
lithuanian lawmaker nikolai medvedev visiting riga said it 
appeared that although the three baltic republics have taken 
different approaches to their independence drives the answer is 
the same 
gorbunov and other latvian leaders have emphasized that latvias 
declaration with its unspecified transition period to full 
independence is calculated to leave the door open to talks 
with the kremlin 
on saturday night latvian communist party chief alfreds rubiks 
said he had spoken with gorbachev that gorbachev ruled out talks 
and was considering sanctions instead 
but latvian politicians and soviet foreign ministry spokesman 
gennady i gerasimov said monday that rubiks account did not 
constitute an official reaction 
godmanis the new prime minister told parliament his economic 
plan included denationalization of some industries rationing of 
some basic foodstuffs and free market prices on most other products 
he said the government would work to strengthen economic 
cooperation among the three baltic republics and foster direct ties 
between latvia and various soviet regions 
thousands of soviet soldiers continued to rehearse for the may 9 
parade in riga celebrating victory in europe in world war ii but 
ivans said latvians were refusing to consider it intimidation such 
as the repeated tank movements used in lithuania to unnerve 
independence activists there 
it might mean a demonstration of force ivans admitted 
but we are trying to approach it very tolerantly 
