specific tax increase as a precondition to agreement 
i think that its a question of walking that plank together 
he said 
many democrats have advocated raising the maximum income tax 
rate to 33 percent for the 600000 wealthiest americans who now 
pay a 28 percent rate some members of both parties have also 
talked about boosting levies on gasoline imported oil cigarettes 
beer and alcohol 
the administration negotiated with members of congress last year 
on a compromise budget but the white house is pursuing a 
bipartisan budget pact even more intensely this year 
fearing that rising interest rates would seriously damage the 
economy the administration initiated the budget talks following 
the recent approval of rival 12 trillion budget propsals by the 
full house of represenatives and the senate budget committee 
bush shares with congressional leaders anxiety over a deficit 
that is fighting every reduction attempt that we can come up 
fitzwater said 
bushs own fiscal 1991 budget was never seriously considered by 
congress and the administration claims both house and senate 
measures would fall short of reducing the deficit over 150 
billion this year to the 64 billion required under the 
grammrudman budgetbalancing law 
failure to make this target will touch off automatic 
acrosstheboard spending cuts 
congressional leaders have said that getting the deficit down to 
the required range to avoid the automatic trigger would almost 
certainly require substantial tax increases 
fitzwaters comments monday generally reflected what 
participants in sunday nights white house meeting had reported 
that bush had assured them everything was on the table 
at his daily briefing for reporters fitzwater repeatedly 
declined to say whether bushs 1988 campaign vow of no new 
taxes was still in force bush has not repeated his promise in 
months 
the president and the leadership tried to come to this with an 
open mind fitzwater said 
he said one of the operating principles bush and the leaders 
mitchell senate republican leader bob dole of kansas house 
speaker thomas s foley dwash and house republican leader 
robert h michel of illinois agreed to was that there are no 
preconditions 
anyone can bring up an issue for discussion and debate 
fitzwater said 
bush and the lawmakers also agreed that they cant negotiate a 
budget in public that it does take a lot of giveandtake and 
moving back and forth so well try to keep a little mystery in the 
marriage 
the spokesman said the leaders also agreed that talks would go 
until we achieve a budget that all sides can agree on 
fitzwater said such details as who would participate in the 
budget talks where they would be held and how active a role the 
president would take had not been decided 
