thousands of israelis demanding electoral 
reform on monday booed legislators as they drove past the crowd to 
reach parliament for the opening of the summer session 
dozens of police officers held back about 4000 protesters as 
they jeered and waved placards reading we are sick of you and 
no less than democracy 
the rally was the latest protest by a growing electoral reform 
movement the protests were sparked by the political horsetrading 
following the march 15 collapse of the ruling coalition of the 
leftleaning labor party and the rightwing likud bloc 
the two rival parties have been trying the past six weeks to 
lure defectors from each others camps with offers of political 
posts and money there were growing signs monday that another 
likudlabor coalition could be in the offing 
israel television reported both parties were considering a 
compromise proposal by the national religious party that would 
avoid a clear yesorno answer to us mideast peace proposals 
the coalition government was toppled by labor after likud 
refused to accept proposals by secretary of state james a baker 
iii that would lead to an israelipalestinian dialogue in cairo 
at the protest rally in front of parliament meanwhile the 
crowd chanted we are fed up as legislators drove past 
the general feeling is that there is nobody who is actually 
representing you said mike marmer a rabbinical student who 
immigrated from london four years ago 
