strong cold winds continued to batter the pacific northwest on 
monday carrying heavy snow that lashed the washington cascades 
flooding continued in arkansas and texas 
weather was mild and sunny over much of the nation with 
unusually high temperatures in parts of the upper plains 
gale warnings were posted over the washington straits and along 
portions of californias northern coast as powerful winds continued 
to pound the region the gusts pushed colder temperatures into the 
northwest during the weekend and brought an early morning 
temperature of 26 degrees to colville wash 
overnight snowfall across the cascades included 12 inches at 
stampede pass there also was snow on the highway through 
snoqualmie pass 
overnight temperatures were expected to drop into the mid 20s in 
the helena valley of montana by midweek 
the arkansas river approached record heights as flooding 
continued in arkansas and texas the river was expected to crest at 
little rock on tuesday and pine bluff on wednesday at levels higher 
than in the devastating flood of april 1973 
on saturday the river crested at van buren ark at the 
highest stage since its navigation system was constructed 
extensive flooding also continued along the white and cache 
rivers in eastern arkansas there was lowland flooding along the 
black and st francis rivers in northeast arkansas as well as 
along the quachita river in southern arkansas 
in northern texas the trinity river was expected to crest near 
trinidad about two feet lower than the record level recorded in 
april 1942 but about 15 feet over flood stage near long lake 
skies were sunny over much of the nation at noon monday 
rainshowers were scattered over central new england from northeast 
pennsylvania into central new york state over eastern upper 
michigan the lower texas gulf coast and southwest wyoming 
rainshowers over south central montana and north central wyoming 
changed to snow at the higher elevations snow mixed with rain also 
fell over northwest montana 
on sunday unseasonably warm weather moved into the eastern 
portion of the northern plains and the mississippi valley noon 
temperatures monday were 15 to 20 degrees warmer than average 
across eastern south dakota and southern minnesota redwood falls 
minn hit 90 degrees by early afternoon 
the low temperature for the nation monday morning was 22 degrees 
at truckee calif 
temperatures around the nation at 3 pm edt ranged from 33 
degrees at yellowstone wyo to 97 degrees at needles calif 
