<TEXT>
a weak prosecution case and 
missing evidence make it unlikely those blamed for the november 
slaying of six jesuit priests and two women will be convicted a 
court source said monday 
the united states has warned el salvador it could face a cutoff 
of 85 million in annual military aid if it fails to actively 
pursue its investigation of the deaths of the priests the house 
foreign relations committee has approved a proposal to that effect 
the source at el salvadors 4th criminal court who insisted on 
anonymity told the associated press he believed col guillermo 
benavides commander of the military school at the time three 
lieutenants and five soldiers charged with the crime stood a good 
chance of being acquitted 
the source said the only evidence introduced against benavides 
is testimony from other suspects under salvadoran law a person 
accused in the same case cannot testify against a codefendant 
the evidence makes it difficult to convict benavides the 
principal suspect the source said 
the difficulties are compounded because the four cadets who 
could testify in the case were sent out of the country the source 
said also a logbook and a personal diary that could document 
benavides movements have been reported by authorities to be lost 
the disclosures regarding the cadets and the diary were made in 
mondays editions of the new york times 
all these problems raised obstacles to the courts effort to 
find out if any other highranking military men are involved or are 
trying to cover up for the murderers the source said 
gen humberto larios the defense minister said sending the 
cadets abroad was part of a project but if the judge 
considers the presence of the cadets convenient they could be 
recalled 
a personal diary that benavides was reported to have kept has 
also not been found the source said the source said benavides 
mentioned the diary out of court but later denied it existed 
no one has seen the diary the court never had possession of 
it as far as i know the source added 
the court also asked the high command for the academy guard 
logbook which would show who entered and left the academy nov 
1516 but the military claimed it was lost the source said 
the six priests their housekeeper and her daughter were rousted 
from their beds by uniformed soldiers at the central american 
university campus the night of nov 16 and shot to death 
the slayings occurred during the worst offensive by leftist 
guerrillas in a decade of civil war the campus branded a bastion 
of leftist thought by conservatives was under military control and 
a dawntodusk curfew at the time of the killings 
the four cadets on guard duty at the military school the night 
of the murders were sent to the united states and panama the court 
source said and when the judge asked them to testify he was told 
they were out of the country 
col sigifredo ochoa perez a retired officer publicly accused 
the military high command of protecting those who ordered the 
killings 
ochoa now a national assembly member from the conservative 
ruling arena party said benavides carried out the slayings on 
orders from above but he did not offer proof 
judge ricardo zamora who is handling the case refused to talk 
to reporters but the source said he recently had a long interview 
with officials of the us embassy 
about 72000 people have been killed in el salvadors civil war 
mostly civilians slain by rightist death squads 
