<TEXT>
nepal on monday abolished a key post that 
preserved the monarchys monopoly on power and a leader of the 
oppositionled government reported nepals king has pledged 
cooperation in working toward democracy 
nepalese christians also demanded an end to a 32yearold law 
banning religious conversion and called for the establishment of a 
secular state in this hindu kingdom 
in an evening radio broadcast prime minister krishna prasad 
bhattarai announced the post of zonal commissioner had been 
abolished 
there are 14 such commissioners in nepal each responsible for 
administering a separate region and appointed by the king the 
nepali congress party which heads the coalition government 
alleges these commisioners were responsible for suppressing 
activists during the recent democracy movement 
the opposition claims hundreds of people were killed during the 
twomonth campaign for multiparty democracy that forced king 
birendra to surrender his stranglehold on political power police 
arrested hundreds of protesters 
nepali congress party secretary general girija prasad koirala 
urged monday that legal action be taken against at least seven 
zonal commissioners who he said were responsible for ordering 
crackdowns on prodemocracy activists 
bhattarai a longtime opposition leader last month was 
appointed head of an interim coalition government made up of 
opposition parties including nepali congress and leftist parties 
the coalition pressed the king to agree to a multiparty system 
and scrap a 29yearold ban on political parties multiparty 
elections are expected within a year 
koirala met the king sunday and said monday that birendra gave 
assurances of his cooperation in drafting a new constitution 
the king also promised bhattarai would have sufficient powers to 
accomplish his task of establishing a democracy koirala said 
the call for greater religious freedom came as 1500 protestants 
kicked off a fiveday religious convention organized by the 
katmandubased nepal christian fellowship 
the convention called for a revision of the 1958 constitution 
that bans religious conversion and urged the government to nullify 
a 1965 law prohibiting proselytism under that law proselytizers 
can be sentenced to up to six years in jail 
convention participants demanded that 29 christians serving 
various jail sentences be immediately released and cases against 
200 other christians dropped 
nepali congress party elder ganesh man singh assured the 
christians that his party which heads the new government would 
release the imprisoned christians and drop charges against the 
others 
nepalese christians say there are 35000 to 40000 christians in 
nepal the government says there are only 3000 
most of the christians are protestants not affiliated with 
international denominations about 90 percent of nepals 17 million 
people are hindus the rest mostly moslem and buddhist 
</TEXT>
