<TEXT>
a centerright party that advocates 
croatias independence from the rest of yugoslavia took a 
commanding lead monday in early returns from the final round of the 
republics first free elections in 50 years 
with partial votes from 95 constituencies counted candidates 
for the croatian democratic union were leading in 48 
constituencies the communists were ahead in 34 districts and 
independents and other smaller parties led in the remaining 13 
the vote is considered crucial to the future of the fragile 
yugoslav federation 
the apparent victory of the croatian democratic union is likely 
to exacerbate political and ethnic tensions with yugoslavias five 
other constituent republics particularly with serbia the 
countrys largest republic 
about 15 million croatians voted sunday and monday in 111 
constituencies throughout the republic for the remaining 225 seats 
in the regions parliament final results were not expected until 
tuesday at earliest 
in the first round of voting april 2223 the democratic union 
won 104 of the 131 seats decided for the 356seat tricameral 
regional parliament 
the croatian communist party renamed the party for democratic 
reform gathered only 13 seats in the first round while the 
centrist coalition for national accord considered a preelection 
favorite won three 
croatians voted for us because we have offered them democracy 
to replace years of oneparty monopoly democratic union leader 
franjo tudjman said in a monday interview 
now we have to start fulfilling everything we promised to our 
voters he said celebrating his apparent victory with champagne 
at the partys zagreb headquarters 
tudjman waged his partys campaign largely on nationalist 
sentiments advocating croatias political and economic 
independence from the rest of yugoslavia 
he says yugoslavias republics should become independent states 
and establish relations only if they have common interests 
the reform communists say the national federation model is 
adequate but if it fails to reflect the republics needs in the 
future yugoslavia should become a confederation without central 
rule 
tudjman 66 became yugoslavias youngest army general but 
later spent five years in jail after being convicted of croatian 
nationalism and hostile activities against the state 
his bid for power has fueled a rivalry between croatia the 
secondlargest republic and serbia that dates to the creation of 
yugoslavia after world war ii 
serbias media strongly influenced by the republics hardline 
communist leaders has accused the democratic union of fascism 
yugoslavia is a loose federation of six republics and two 
autonomous provinces torn by ethnic and ideological tensions 
croatia and slovenia are pushing for democratic reforms and 
closer ties with the west the centerright demos coalition won 
aprils free parliamentary elections in slovenia and is 
establishing the first noncommunist regional government in 
yugoslavia in more than 40 years 
serbia and montenegro have not legalized opposition parties 
macedonia and bosnia plan free elections this year 
