<TEXT>
france broke an agreement with new zealand by 
repatriating two french spies convicted in the 1985 bombing of the 
greenpeace flagship rainbow warrior a special tribunal ruled 
monday 
but it rejected new zealands demand that the two be made to 
serve their full sentences on a remote pacific atoll the panel 
instead recommended france pay 2 million to a fund to encourage 
friendly ties between the two countries 
new zealands prime minister geoffrey palmer said that 
although the french agents were let off the decision was a victory 
for new zealand 
the time has come to put this whole sorry tawdry episode 
behind us its dominated the relationship between france and new 
zealand since july 1985 palmer told reporters in wellington 
he said however that new zealand would continue to oppose 
french nuclear testing in the south pacific the rainbow warrior 
was to have led a protest flotilla toward a test site on the south 
pacific atoll of mururoa 
the french foreign ministry which announced the panels 
conclusions said it marked the end of the affair it said 
relations between france and new zealand could now develop in the 
traditional spirit of friendship 
the tribunal was set up after france brought home intelligence 
agents alain mafart and dominique prieur both of whom were 
convicted of manslaughter by new zealand courts 
they had been sentenced to 10year prison terms each for their 
roles in the july 1985 sinking of the rainbow warrior in auckland 
harbor in which a greenpeace photographer was killed 
under a unsponsored accord reached in july 1986 the 
sentences of the two french agents were commuted to 3year terms 
to be served on the pacific atoll of hao an isolated french 
military base the accord also ordered france to pay 7 million in 
reparations to new zealand 
france brought home mafart in december 1987 and prieur in may 
1988 
the tribunal concluded in a majority ruling that france did 
not violate the accord when it repatriated mafart for health 
reasons without consulting new zealand but it said france 
committed a substantial violation by not returning him to the 
base later 
it also ruled france committed substantial violations when 
it brought prieur home also without consultations due to her 
pregnancy and her fathers poor health she was not returned to the 
atoll either 
even so the tribunal ruled that france was no longer obliged to 
return either officer to the atoll because its obligations expired 
in july 1989 when the pairs threeyear terms would have ended 
the tribunal was presided over by dr eduardo jimenez de 
arechaga of uruguay a former president of the international court 
of justice and two arbitors chosen by france and new zealand 
they were prof jeandenis bredin picked by france and sir 
kenneth keith chosen by new zealand 
keith in an addendum to the decision said he disagreed that 
french obligations expired with the scheduled end of the sentences 
and argued that the two should finish their terms 
he also disagreed with the conclusion that mafarts evacuation 
without consultation was acceptable 
 
</TEXT>
