st regis catholic church for 32yearold harold edwards 
he was killed may 1 in a gunbattle near a barricade in snye 
quebec another mohawk was killed near the same barricade on the 
reservation which straddles the uscanadian border 
some mohawks oppose casino gambling and bingo as an unwanted 
outside influence supporters note the gambling earns needed cash 
for the reservation 
outsiders efforts to end the violence are complicated by the 
contention of some mohawks rejection of state and federal 
jurisdiction on their land 
a team of 10 mediators from the us justice department met for 
several hours with representatives from the reservations elected 
councils on the american and canadian sides as well as the council 
of hereditary chiefs 
the meeting was held to lay the groundwork for negotiations to 
try to end the 9monthold gambling dispute said brenda lafrance 
a spokeswoman for an antigambling faction on the reservation she 
said those negotiations could begin tuesday 
indians at mondays meeting also were expected to respond to 
gov mario cuomos call for the st regis tribal council to create 
its own police force which could eventually operate on both sides 
of the border 
they expressed an interest to respond to the governors 
proposal said dan gaspe a spokesman for antigambling indian 
leaders 
the tribal police force was abolished in 1981 since then there 
has been no local law enforcement on the american side of the 
reservation called akwesasne where the partridge drums by 
mohawks 
mohawks on both sides of the gambling dispute attended edwards 
funeral which was closed to reporters 
there have been no arrests in either death but canadian 
provincial police say they expect to make a major announcement 
sometime this week about the murder investigation 
cuomo said monday in albany that he would keep state police on 
the reservation while he and tribal officials discuss setting up an 
indian police force 
the governor also said conditions at the reservation may have 
improved to the point where direct negotiations over allowing some 
form of legalized gambling could begin 
about 200 refugees from the canadian side of the reservation 
remained sheltered monday at the transport canada dormitory in 
cornwall ontario they are the last of a group who fled their 
homes last week after violence flared 
