each year between the winter capital jammu in the south and the 
summer capital srinagar 
commandos lined the streets and troops placed barricades outside 
government buildings government workers were moved to work in 
police vehicles accompanied by troops in jeeps and trucks 
bands of moslem youths stoned some of the vehicles and youths 
snatched the identity cards of government workers 
a citywide strike called by moslem separatist groups brought 
the city to a standstill shops and businesses remained closed 
throughout the day 
posters on the walls of srinagar had called the strike to 
protest the annual movement of the capital and warned of reprisals 
if the order was ignored most moslem government workers stayed 
away from their jobs official sources said 
sporadic gunfire echoed through the city and a curfew relaxation 
in several areas of srinagar was cut short because of violence 
police said 
the crisis in kashmir has heightened tension and animosity 
between largely hindu india and moslem pakistan 
india accuses pakistan of harboring and arming the separatists 
pakistan denies the charge and says india is brutally crushing a 
movement for selfdetermination 
the two countries went to war over the kashmir valley in 1948 
and again in 1965 both nations have claimed kashmir since they won 
their independence from britain in 1947 
the old princely state of kashmir was mostly moslem but its 
ruler was hindu and he opted to join india 
sixtyfour percent of jammukashmirs 6 million people are 
moslems hindus comprise 82 percent of indias 880 million people 
moslems make up 12 percent of india 
</TEXT>
