a heart transplant patient put on a 
heartassist mechanism after its use was restricted to lastresort 
cases died monday of multiple organ failure 
darwin kramer 65 died minutes after the two symbion inc 
assist devices which had pumped blood through his transplanted 
heart since april 17 and other life support were disconnected 
said university medical center spokesman george martinez 
martinez said the cause of death was multiple organ failure 
richard smith umcs chief biomedical engineer in charge of 
artificial heart and assist devices said the symbion devices had 
functioned well and caused no problems 
in january the us food and drug administration withdrew 
approval of symbion artificial hearts and heartassist devices 
citing safety concerns in february the fda said it would allow 
their use as a last resort 
kramer of scottsdale received his new heart march 10 when his 
body began to reject it the two symbion acute ventricular devices 
called a bivad were implanted to let the donor heart recover 
smith said 
the bivad which sits on the abdomen and is connected to the 
heart by tubes through the chest helped kramer stabilize martinez 
said 
but about five days ago doctors discovered a systemic infection 
of unknown cause when kramer lapsed into multiple organ failure 
and doctors saw no hope for recovery his family was consulted and 
life support disconnected smith said 
kramer had been a candidate for another donor heart since april 
28 when doctors determined his rejection of the first one was 
irreversible 
kramers bivad implant was the second done on a heart recipient 
by dr jack g copeland head of umcs transplant program but his 
first use of a symbion device since the fda action 
smith said the first umc transplant patient to receive bivad 
support had the device for 10 days after her donor heart failed to 
start 
the heart recovered and the woman is alive more than a year 
later he said 
