a state appeals court has rejected a 
bid by freedom newspapers inc shareholder harry hoiles to dissolve 
the 1 billion media group 
the court in a ruling made public may 1 upheld a 1987 decision 
issued by superior court judge leonard goldstein that found no 
basis in hoiles claim that onethird of the familyoperated 
corporation illegally was undermined by the twothirds majority 
the lawsuit stems from hoiles claim that his sister mary jane 
hoiles hardie promised to back him as the successor to harrys 
older brother clarence who headed freedom until his death in 1981 
but she refused to back him and harry hoiles talked to 
potential buyers for his shares including the rival times mirror 
co 
his sister and other family members offered to buy out his 
shares at an offer that reflected a minority discount harry hoiles 
said the 125 million offer was insufficient 
concerned about a possible stock sale to competitors the 
majority shareholders adopted a stock restriction to give the 
hardies and the family of clarence hoiles the first chance to buy 
each others stock 
harry hoiles also was not reelected to a threemember executive 
committee of freedom 
he sued alleging the actions had denied him a fair price for 
his stock and devalued it 
but goldstein ruled the majority stockholders had acted legally 
and the appellate court agreed 
fairness does not require the majority to submit to corporate 
blackmail at the whim of a minority any more than it will permit a 
majority to take unfair advantage of a minority wrote associate 
justice thomas f crosby jr 
harry hoiles lawyer kenneth scholtz said unless the appellate 
court grants a rehearing he will seek review before the state 
supreme court 
