<TEXT>
a former city prosecutor won a record 34 
million libel award may 3 from the philadelphia inquirer but a 
media lawyer and a reporters group said the judgment will likely be 
overturned on appeal 
the judgment was the largest ever awarded against the news 
media surpassing the 28 million a heart surgeon won last month 
from a san antonio television station according to henry kaufman 
general counsel of the libel defense resource center in new york 
common pleas court jurors awarded 25 million in compensatory 
damages and 315 million in punitive damages to attorney richard 
a sprague a former first assistant district attorney 
sprague sued in 1983 over articles dating to 1973 in the 
inquirer which has won 17 pulitzer prizes in 16 years many for 
investigative stories 
i am a very strong advocate of first amendment rights said 
james e beasley attorney for sprague what i dont tolerate and 
i dont think society should tolerate is the use of investigative 
reporters or the power of the press for a personal vendetta and 
that is what developed here 
sprague sued over stories questioning his actions and decisions 
as a prosecutor 
he contended that greg walter one of the reporters involved in 
the stories had threatened to get and destroy sprague who had 
prosecuted walter in 1972 for taping a conversation without the 
other persons knowledge 
walter has since died 
beasley said the jurys verdict after deliberations of 2 hours 
at the end of the 11week trial before judge charles p mirarchi 
jr sent a message to investigative reporters not to destroy 
somebodys reputation 
we will of course appeal eugene l roberts jr executive 
editor and president of the newspaper said in a statement and i 
am confident that however long it takes the inquirer will prevail 
most of our case never got to the jury thirteen witnesses 
were eliminated by judge mirarchi and an investigative report by 
the then state attorney general that supported the inquirer story 
was not allowed into evidence 
sprague sued over articles that he said implied he was involved 
in an illegal wiretapping incident an allegation he denied and 
questioned his role in a homicide case involving a son of a friend 
former state police commissioner rocco urella an eightweek trial 
resulted in a 45 million verdict for sprague in 1983 
the state supreme court in june 1988 ordered a new trial 
declaring reporters have an absolute right to invoke the state 
shield law in refusing to identify confidential sources during 
legal proceedings 
in the original trial judge charles a lord ruled the law did 
not apply in the case and excluded all testimony about information 
from unidentified sources 
its unimaginable to me that a punitive damage award in this 
amount could or would be upheld said floyd abrams a prominent 
first amendment lawyer he represents nbc in appealing a 53 
million libel judgment won by entertainer wayne newton 
this is another example of libel law running amok abrams 
said i think that this case and others will sooner rather than 
later lead the supreme court to address the constitutionality of 
punitive damages in libel cases 
jane kirtley executive director of the reporters committee for 
freedom of the press sees a first amendment issue in such awards 
all a punitive damage award is when its awarded against a 
news organization is a fine for speaking she said but beyond 
that it doesnt have to bear any relationship to anything 
</TEXT>
