all but 5000 from each man was to go to attorneys fees and 
court costs 
their cases were dismissed last year and the herald countersued 
claiming the lawsuits were frivolous 
rosenbaum and ramirez filed suit in connection with political 
advertisements the newspaper ran when rosenbaum was running for the 
county commission in 1988 
the men who also sued rosenbaums opponent ray ramon claimed 
that the herald and ramon conspired to run a political ad in which 
ramirez endorsed ramon for county commissioner 
according to the lawsuits the herald published the ad while 
knowing the information to be false 
after the suits were dismissed the newspaper filed and won the 
counterclaim against rosenbaum and ramirez 
state district judge robert f barnes said in his april 5 ruling 
that the complaints were totally without merit the judge said 
that the newspaper was entitled to additional damages as sanctions 
its our intent to countersue for damages and attorneys fees 
any time were faced with this kind of legal action said doug 
hardie herald publisher 
a large portion of those are frivolous lawsuits a large 
portion of those are politically motivated in an attempt to control 
what newspapers and television stations report he said 
