teamsters newspaper division leaders 
approved a resolution may 2 asking the international union to 
support drivers and other employees of the new york daily news who 
have been without a contract since the end of march 
the vote came after michael j alvino president of the 
newspaper and mail deliverers union one of 10 within the allied 
printing trades council told teamsters the council was in the 
front lines of a struggle to break organized labor in the nations 
largest mostunionized city 
if the news beats the printing unions then every other union 
whatever they deliver whatever it is they will be taken on by 
their employers alvino said 
john p kennedy president of the pressmens union another 
allied affiliate said unionbusting tactics perfected in smaller 
cities since the 1960s were being tried in new york 
this is going to be seen all over the country and were going 
to stop them he said 
alvino denied a strike was imminent if the washingtonbased 
teamsters sided with the new york unions he said his attorney was 
studying the papers latest offer a threeyear contract with wage 
increases of 5 percent the first year and 4 percent in each 
successive year 
however alvino said the offer based on the current 2038 an 
hour for a 35hour week was a veiled attempt to destroy his 
98yearold union and added that a counterproposal was likely 
the daily news also seeks managementrights and nostrike 
clauses and the exclusion of all side agreements not included in 
the new contract it says it must be able to weed out 
featherbedding in the pressmens and drivers unions in order to 
turn a profit 
the offer was revealed may 1 the drivers are to respond at a 
may 14 bargaining session 
