<TEXT>
each wednesday morning a crowd gathers in a 
parking lot on the southwest corner of toledo outside the basement 
of our lady of lourdes 
as the church doors open bob and ginny pacholski assume their 
posts behind the soup kitchen serving counter just as they have 
every wednesday for eight years 
we thought wed do this for two or three years at the most 
until the recession ended says pacholski who opened his 
hospitality kitchen in 1982 
now though theres no end in sight 
roughly 600 men women and children make their way through the 
food line every week so many that the pacholskis must assign them 
all numbers and serve them in shifts the overflow crowd stands 
patiently outside the door waiting to be called over the 
microphone bob uses to keep things moving 
the long cafeteria tables are packed and the traffic between 
serving line tables and door is heavy the majority of clients are 
single men old women and mothers with young children although a 
number of twoparent families are here too 
we treat people with dignity says pacholski a retired real 
estate agent hes tanned and fitlooking with kindly blue eyes 
that continually sweep the tables searching for empty seats 
clinking flatware scraping chairs and the muffled roar of 
dozens of conversations fill the room once the schools let out in 
june the number of children will skyrocket and noise levels will 
increase appreciably 
like most soup kitchens the pacholskis does not require its 
clients to show identification those receiving the boxes of 
federal surplus commodities being dispensed at the far end of the 
room are required to prove need with unemployment compensation 
cards or other such documentation 
it used to be all general relief or afdc aid to families with 
dependent children now were seeing people unemployed people 
laid off pacholski says 
the first week we opened we had 23 people by that august we 
had 1013 lately in a typical month the kitchen serves 2400 
people although the numbers are once again going up 
todays menu includes barbecued pork sandwiches made of canned 
pork from the us department of agriculture as well as chicken 
spaghetti rice corn broccoli peaches rolls doughnuts and 
cookies pacholski shops at the toledo seagate food bank which 
collects edible but unmarketable food for use by nonprofit 
agencies at minimal cost 
behind the serving counter are several donated birthday cakes 
nobody seems to mind the smudged icing judging from the number of 
celebrants lining up to pick out cakes theyre very popular 
bob says with a salesmans pride 
regulars at the soup kitchen include 70yearold marcile battle 
who until recently was supporting eight children along with her 
92yearold mother on a 182 monthly social security check and 63 
worth of food stamps 
three of the children are cousins girls aged 8 5 and 3 the 
5yearold was 3 days old when she came to me the 8yearold was 2 
months says mrs battle who says shes been declared ineligible 
for welfare benefits 
the other kids had parents but they left the kids with me in 
july of 1989 they said they were going to a funeral that funeral 
never did end 
a social worker from childrens services finally picked up the 
children bringing the size of mrs battles family back down to 
five she says situations like hers arent unusual and blames them 
on toledos drug problem 
the weekly lunch at the hospitality kitchen and the carefully 
wrapped leftovers she carries home help stretch her meager food 
budget says mrs battle whose husband died three years ago no 
matter how strapped she is i always share 
food stamps buy me one trip to the grocery store and the 
groceries last til the middle of the month i cant keep up with 
the bills its hard 
though grateful for the help the pacholskis gave her mrs 
battle says she finds eating at the soup kitchen hard 
i would prefer to buy my own groceries i like to try to feed 
my own self id rather any day to help someone else than to have 
someone else helping me 
