<TEXT>
but i keep up the vigil anyway outside the local 
elementary school 
my 4yearold daughter rebecca schiffres is determined to 
attend lafayette with her big brother ethan but there is only 
room for 40 children in the two prekindergarten classes and if i 
leave my post under the schools portico i give up my chance to get 
one of them 
its 345 am i have been there since 830 the night before i 
stretch out on a borrowed lawn chair wrapping myself in a sleeping 
bag that had not been used for 15 years i cannot get to sleep 
all around me four dozen other parents wait a lone man paces 
on the school courtyard while someone shoots hoops on the 
basketball court around back a few people use flashlights to read 
the silence is broken by a few snores from some of those 
fortunate enough to sleep and the whispered conversations of those 
who couldnt 
i havent done anything like this since 1969 when the amazing 
mets got into the world series and i tried to get into the 
ballpark i was in high school then and staying up all night was 
pure excitement 
not anymore 
why then are we all here camping out on a rainy night hoping to 
win a cherished spot in a public elementary school in the district 
of columbia a city not known for educational excellence 
preschool programs abound in an area where the majority of 
mothers work outside the home the good ones fill up fast ask 
marty crutsinger aps economics writer who has survived four 
allnighters to get his 4yearold daughter elizabeth into a 
churchrun preschool in suburban virginia 
whats different about the lafayette vigil is that were waiting 
to get our children into a public school 
the school board has mandated that there be at least one 
prekindergarten class in each of the citys 124 elementary 
schools some schools including lafayette have added a second 
but its not always enough 
if people knew that there were enough prekindergarten 
programs for everyone then there wouldnt be the panic says 
maurice sykes the districts director of early childhood programs 
but theres not enough money to accommodate everyone he says 
sykes attributes the high demand to the second baby boom 
reaching school age the phenomena of working parents the fullday 
program and the price 
the reason those slots become coveted is because we became 
part of the day care network sykes said if you can provide a 
service for free thats when you get competitive 
as for the allnight vigils he says no one is satisfied with 
the system were trying to figure out a reasonable equitable 
solution 
three years ago when we considered signing ethan up for 
prekindergarten i arrived at 910 the morning of registration and 
got no 32 in the ensuing years parents have lined up earlier and 
earlier to guarantee themselves a slot 
last year people who showed up at dawn still got into the 
