editors note even as communism crumbles in much of the rest 
of the world robert mugabe is still adamant about establishing a 
oneparty marxistleninist state in zimbabwe formerly rhodesia 
while that makes a lot of businessmen and others uneasy few 
dispute mugabes successes in social reforms that have largely 
bettered the lot of his people 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when former guerrilla chieftain robert 
mugabe led rhodesia to independence as blackgoverned zimbabwe 10 
years ago he faced a daunting task 
the economy of the former whiteled nation was in tatters 
racial tensions were rife civil war loomed in matabeleland 
stronghold of opposition leader joshua nkomo and mugabes support 
for south african guerrillas raised the risk of a backlash from 
pretorias whiteled government a break in his main trade routes 
through that country or even a military strike 
zimbabwe on april 18 celebrated the 10th anniversary of 
independence from britain with military marches and tribal dancing 
speaking to a crowd at a stadium outside harare mugabe said he 
welcomed the expiration of the 10year constitution brokered by the 
british that contained entrenched racial provisions protecting 
the interests of the 90000strong white community 
he said the second decade of independence would witness even 
greater moves toward unity peace and progress 
few dispute that during those first 10 years zimbabwe made 
remarkable progress in the areas of education and health care 
now comes the hard part 
unemployment is at record levels along with urban crime vague 
economic planning has led to rampant inflation shortages of 
essential commodities and deterioration of the national transport 
system 
and mugabes vow to transform one of africas few westernstyle 
democracies into a oneparty marxistleninist state has split the 
ruling zimbabwe african national union patriotic front and 
divided the countrys 92 million people 
it has also alarmed local businessmen and foreign governments 
some question whether the onetime schoolteacher is on the right 
political track as his old eastern european models undergo radical 
reforms 
he is obsessed with a unitary system a member of the 
partys 160member central committee told the associated press on 
condition of anonymity but by no means does he have all the 
support he needs in the party or cabinet unless he stampedes it 
through 
oneparty rule has been mugabes dream since he was held for a 
decade as a political prisoner by the last white rhodesian prime 
minister ian d smith at that time it was a fashionable system 
in eastern europe and much of the third world 
with that system largely discredited abroad mugabes own 
credibility is at stake but mugabe wont budge 
the multiparty system spells the destruction of our nation 
he said last year we believe we are one people one flag one 
identity why shouldnt we have one party 
mugabe won distinction as an eloquent chairman for three years 
of the 102member nonaligned movement of developing nations an 
alternative to the east and west power blocs 
no one ever expected the nonaligned movement to do anything 
really tangible says a western diplomat in harare but mugabe 
made all the right noises and his chairmanship was a great success 
in those terms 
the zimbabwean leader habitually clad in dark suits that match 
his businesslike manner exercises the impatient authority of an 
austere headmaster 
associates say he is sharply intolerant of those who challenge 
him but he rewards loyalty richly 
he rarely exposes his human side except on occasional visits to 
the mudandgrass hut villages in the countryside that remind him 
of his own birthplace 
a teetotaler and nonsmoker with a fondness for hot spicy 
foods mugabe enjoys watching the sedate english game of cricket 
he works out daily at state house on a static exercise bike and 
relaxes near a hifi to songs from the 1950s pat boone being a 
favorite 
a blinking stare from behind thick spectacles hides stiff 
mannerisms he sports a toothbrush mustache and in common with 
many african men his age he dyes his hair to conceal specks of 
gray 
educated at a roman catholic mission mugabe is described by 
church leaders as an ascetic with high moral principles however 
he is no longer a practicing catholic like his aged mother and his 
ghanaianborn wife sally who all attend mass regularly 
yet hes comfortable in the company of clerics according to the 
rev oscar wermter spokesman for the catholic bishops conference 
which opposes his oneparty state objective 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900507-0201 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
he shares our concerns for moral and social justice wermter 
says but when it comes to the freedom of political choice as a 
fundamental human right thats where we part company 
wermter and others fear mugabe may be sealing his own fate by 
pursuing his marxist goal 
we are afraid from the african experience that oneparty 
states normally end in military coups because there is no other 
mechanism for change he says 
relations between church and state were not always cozy 
in 1984 mugabe vilified church leaders who accused north 
koreantrained zimbabwean troops of atrocities in the western 
matabeleland province where armed rebels loyal to nkomo posed a 
threat to the government 
thousands of civilians were killed wounded or driven into exile 
in operations against the dissidents 
but the remaining 120 rebels laid down their guns under an 
amnesty that followed a unity pact between nkomo and mugabe in 
december 1988 
nkomo a former political foe now turned friend is to be sworn 
in as one of two vicepresidents this year 
but his promotion from senior minister may not mollify 
supporters of nkomos defunct zimbabwe african peoples union 
which has merged with the ruling party says masipula sithole a 
ustrained professor of political studies at the university of 
zimbabwe 
some exzapu officials from the minority ndebele tribe 30 
percent of the population are already disenchanted with the 
disproportionately small role they say they play in government 
sithole says 
sithole says mugabes popularity is increasingly being viewed as 
vain moody paranoid and isolated from the people 
he has no children an only son died at age 6 while mugabe was 
in prison 
mugabe lives behind high walls capped with coils of razor wire 
he travels in a highspeed motorcade escorted by police cars with 
wailing sirens motorcycle outriders and a jeepload of soldiers 
armed with machine guns and automatic rifles 
mugabe who won several college degrees while in detention is 
an admirer of executed romanian dictator nicolai ceaucescu kim il 
sung of north korea and fidel castro of cuba he argues that 
democratic oneparty rule eliminates tribal and ideological 
divisions that hamper the development of third world nations 
it is absurd to argue that democracy exists in a oneparty 
state sithole says 
yet mugabe makes no attempt to conceal his distaste for 
opposition before recent elections he spoke darkly about reports 
that influential whites were backing opposition politicians if 
whites rear their ugly terrorist head we will chop that head 
off he declared 
but on another occasion talking about his image abroad mugabe 
smiled and said look i am not a monster i havent eaten 
anyone 
few people including the 90000 whites who remain from a peak 
of 270000 in the mid1970s dispute mugabes successes in social 
reforms that have largely bettered the lot of his people 
infant mortality dropped as some 450 new rural clinics were 
built and 70 percent of all children were immunized against disease 
high school enrollment swelled ninefold to 695000 and primary 
school attendances doubled to 12 million 
in his anniversary speech mugabe said that apart from wheat 
imports zimbabwe is selfsufficient in food he also praised local 
industries mainly in the hands of white entrepreneurs 
manufacturers generate nearly 30 percent of the gross domestic 
product of about 4 billion he said 
but today unemployment is estimated at almost 25 percent 
only western investment and effective trade liberalization will 
ease the unemployment and an inflation rate of 22 percent annually 
says leading black businessman sam gozo 
but you cant have proper investment and liberalization where 
marxism is the order of the day he says it just wont fly 
despite recent reforms in neighboring south africa and an 
easing of regional tensions with blackruled states a strong 
economic union between the two countries is unlikely while mugabe 
remains a vocal critic of apartheid and an advocate of trade 
embargoes against pretoria 
whether mugabe likes it or not our survival will go 
handinhand with the fortunes of south africa gozo says 
 
