editors note the first spring publishers list of the decade 
is loaded with books on sex and love many looking at what the aids 
threat has done to the sexual revolution with some hints at what 
the future holds here is a sampling 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sex in the 1990s what are we in for 
the naughty nineties the nice nineties 
a recent spate of books on sex love and related matters about 
one title a day came out in february alone could offer hints at 
the sexual mores of the next 10 years 
but many of them look more at where we are coming from rather 
than where we are going 
in mayflower manners etiquette for consenting adults 
former madam sidney biddle barrows brings up the delicate matter of 
good breeding and condoms 
is it assumed she asks that the man will provide them 
is it therefore rude of the woman to preempt that sacred 
responsibility by producing them herself 
this is definitely a nineties question in the world war ii era 
of rosie the riveter even to hint that a woman carried a supply of 
condoms in her pocketbook was decidedly bad form it was absolutely 
unspeakable in the 1930s the decade of the censorious hays office 
in hollywood and a prudish motion picture code 
but may 6 1960 was apparently a pivotal date in the history of 
american sex on that day say jane and michael stern coauthors 
of sixties people the federal drug administration declared 
enovid the first birth control pill safe for prescription sales 
within six years one out of five women of childbearing age 
had a prescription sixties people were infatuated with the pill 
it was a prime symbol of modern life in general 
thanks to the pill carefree sex became yet another of the 
futuristic possibilities that the new decade offered a girl on the 
pill could have sex any time she pleased 
and so we find this passage in daniel mark epsteins loves 
compass a natural history of the heart which contains 
recollections of life and love in the 60s 
when madeline returned to the little college town in the 
autumn of my junior year we found each other at once i tried 
to assure madeline that i would love her as she deserved to be 
loved and in the true spirit of the 1960s we became lovers 
without further ceremony or preamble 
sex out of wedlock adds epstein was simply forbidden 
until the 1960s when we legitimized it per force majeure by 
resacralizing erotic love such an experience as ours may never be 
normal again 
for homosexuals too the world has changed in recent decades as 
many came out into the open but with aids the nineties offer the 
bleak prospect that life for gays may never be the same again 
as allan berube argues in coming out under fire gay men and 
women in world war ii the war itself thanks strangely enough 
to the growing power of psychiatrists was a setback for the gay 
community 
traditionally the military had never officially excluded or 
discharged homosexuals from its ranks says berube but in 
world war ii a dramatic change occurred as psychiatrists increased 
their authority in the armed forces they developed new screening 
procedures to discover and disqualify homosexual men 
the generation of gay men and women who served in world war ii 
grew into adulthood fighting one war for their country and another 
to protect themselves from their governments escalating 
mobilization against them 
half a century later it is a different and deadlier war for the 
nations homosexuals 
there are an estimated 12 million gay men in the united 
states many of whom seek longterm committed relationships in the 
face of the aids epidemic says the publisher of rik isensees 
love between men enhancing intimacy and keeping your 
relationships alive a clinical social worker in san francisco 
isensee deals with such things as what to do when a lover has 
aids 
could this disease in fact become the bubonic plague of the 
1990s the 20th century version of the black death that wiped out a 
third of europe in the 14th century 
more than a million americans are infected with hiv human 
immunodeficiency virus of these statistics indicate that 20 
percent to 50 percent will develop aids within five years 
according to dr alan brauer and his wife donna j brauer who run 
the brauer medical and health center in palo alto calif 
curiously the brauers dire scenario appears in their jointly 
written the eso ecstasy program which the publisher bills as 
the sensual guide for the nineties 
noting that orgasm is totally safe this hefty work explains 
step by step in relentless detail how to achieve eso extended 
sexual orgasm in a methodical 12week program of sexual exercises 
in the 13th week the reader then comes to a chapter titled beyond 
ecstasy 
another medical writer questions whether sex is really a 
necessary ingredient of love at all 
is love always sexually connected asks dr theodore isaac 
rubin md in real love what it is and how to find it he 
says the answer is no 
heterosexual men can love heterosexual men heterosexual women 
can love heterosexual women i disagree with those freudians who 
believe that there is always a sexual current or correlation 
present 
love concludes rubin the author of a couple of 
bestselling books and a frequent guest on tv shows can be 
sexual or nonsexual 
love set free at last in the 1990s from the tyranny of lust 
how much was hoped from sex how little sex can deliver 
professor camille paglia observes in her massive study sexual 
personae art and decadence from nefertiti to emily dickinson 
take as an example emily dickinson herself the new england 
poet says paglia associate professor of humanities at 
philadelphia college of the performing arts is the american 
sade she is frightening this shy victorian spinster was a male 
genius and visionary sadist a fictive sexual persona of towering 
force 
as archie bunker that amiable television bigot of the 1970s 
once said sex used to be up in the mind thats where it 
belongs 
</TEXT>
