<TEXT>
curt dempster champions the oneact play an art 
form embraced by playwrights but usually ignored by broadway 
eugene oneill wrote a lot of oneacts so did tennessee 
williams and joe orton neil simon turned out plaza suite and 
california suite david mamet still writes oneacts so do 
arthur miller harold pinter christopher durang tom stoppard and 
others 
but except for simons efforts the works rarely get to 
broadway oneact plays considered death at the box office are 
the stepchildren of the commercial theater and most of the time 
they are not part of the regular subscription seasons at the 
countrys larger regional or nonprofit theaters either 
oneact plays flourish however at festivals celebrations that 
offer everything from simple readings to fully staged productions 
and there are scores of them across the country according to the 
theater communications group a national organization for 
nonprofit professional theater 
from the tennessee williams new orleans literary festival 
oneact play contest to the minnesota oneact play festival to the 
national oneact play contest by actors theater of louisville to 
the young playwrights festival in new york they all celebrate the 
short drama 
one of the bestknown is the oneact marathon run by dempster at 
new yorks ensemble studio theater a small theater company located 
in an old west side furniture warehouse a block from the hudson 
river 
this offoffbroadway theater founded by dempster in 1971 does 
a lot of other things est with a staff of about 35 full and 
parttime employees presents fulllength works and staged readings 
each year but the jewel in its theatrical crown is its annual 
sixweek marathon of oneact plays 
this years festival began in early may and runs until june 20 
among the wellknown writers represented by the 12 oneacts spread 
over three separate evenings are mamet frank d gilroy john ford 
noonan romulus linney and joyce carol oates but there are 
newcomers too such as 24yearold paul weitz and susan kim who 
is having her first professional production anywhere 
among the oneacts being done this year are a bluestinged 
1990s version of hamlet by shel silverstein eulogy for 
mister hamm a short musical by michael john lachiusa set in a 
seedy hotel and tonight we love a comedy by romulus linney 
about love in a nursing home 
ensemble studio theater which dempster heads as artistic 
director began its oneact festival in 1978 at that time they 
were all alone dempster says now there are nearly a dozen oneact 
festivals in new york alone 
we wanted to focus attention on the neglect the oneact had 
fallen into he recalls we wanted to restore it to its place 
in literature 
most of the oneacts est performs are by its playwriting unit 
which now numbers about 60 members but the theater which has a 
yearly budget of about 800000 also looks at oneact plays sent 
in by regional theaters and unknown writers 
we get a couple thousand a year dempster says play 
readers go through them and evaluate them 
after the number is cut to about 100 the est staff reads them 
and the number is sliced to 40 after more discussions the list is 
cut to 20 finalists and then 12 plays are chosen from that group 
its a long process that takes all year to do dempster 
says theres some yelling and screaming im sort of like the 
president but have an unofficial gentlemans agreement with a 
committee of artist members they have a veto over one play that i 
may love and they hate and if i hate a play they all love i can 
veto that the plays we finally have up on stage are plays we can 
all support 
with all the material coming in the readers tend to notice fads 
or trends 
those types of plays dont tend to get into the marathon 
because they usually are plays that are topical ideas rather than 
artistic ideas dempster says like child abuse plays or plays 
about alcoholism phone sex and incest plays are big now we 
probably read 20 plays a year on incest 
if somebody writes a play now about alcoholism i say did 
you ever read come back little sheba by william inge 
dempster says thats a wonderful little realistic american 
play about a man whos an alcoholic and it says everything you can 
say about the tragedy of alcoholism if you cant do better than 
that why write one 
things looked up for the lowly oneact play in new york this 
season there were several major collections of oneacts at 
lincoln center artistic director gregory mosher paired mamets 
bobby gould in hell with the devil and billy markham by 
shel silverstein two devilishly funny oneacters 
the new york shakespeare festival currently has a big success 
with spunk a trio of plays adapted by george c wolfe from 
three stories by the black writer zora neale hurston it also is 
doing caryl churchills hot fudge pairing it with a short 
twoact play by the same playwright called what else ice 
cream and manhattan theater club revived terrence mcnallys zany 
double bill that went under the collective title of bad habits 
</TEXT>
