<TEXT>
playboy enterprises inc on monday unveiled a 
recapitalization plan aimed at helping the company finance 
acquisitions and other activities without diluting the controlling 
stake of founder hugh hefner 
the recapitalization subject to shareholder approval would 
establish two classes of common stock including a new class of 
nonvoting stock it would increase the number of outstanding 
playboy shares from 15 million to 375 million including 30 
million shares of nonvoting stock the company said 
the plan would not dilute the holdings of hefner who owns 706 
percent of the current outstanding common shares and said he would 
vote to approve the plan 
under its present structure playboy could not raise money by 
selling additional common stock without making the stake held by 
hefner who is chairman emeritus and playboy magazine editor in 
chief relatively smaller 
we believe that the proposed recapitalization will provide 
playboy with increased flexibility to use equity in future 
acquisitions financings and employee benefit plans without 
diluting the voting power of existing stockholders said christie 
hefner playboys chairman and chief executive officer in a 
telephone interview 
playboy stock rose 12 cents to 1287 a share in new york 
stock exchange trading 
under the plan playboy stockholders will receive half of a 
class a voting share for each of their current playboy shares 
followed by a dividend of three nonvoting class b shares for each 
of the class a shares their received in the split 
the recapitalization includes a minority protection feature 
designed to help ensure that the two classes of stock trade at 
approximately equal market prices ms hefner said the provision 
requires that anyone wanting to buy a specific voting position of 
the class a voting stock must buy a proportionate amount of the 
nonvoting shares 
some industry analysts said the plan already adopted by 
playboys board of directors reflects the publishing and video 
companys renewed financial vigor 
playboy last week reported net income of 554000 for its third 
fiscal quarter up from from 262000 a year earlier for the nine 
months ended march 31 net income was 6 million including a 48 
million gain on the sale of the assets of its boarts international 
inc subsidiary compared with 22 million in the yearearlier 
period 
i really see the recap as another building block that having 
established a base of profitability we now are looking ahead to 
the 90s with an eye to expanding internationally in both 
publishing and entertainment and doing that with other 
companies said ms hefner 
after succeeding with the playboy late night television 
series in europe playboy has begun talks with foreign and domestic 
production companies about possibly coproducing television 
programs ms hefner said 
playboy is the sole producer of playboy late night a weekly 
television magazineformat series that debuted in france last 
september and now appers in 10 countries 
playboy also is talking with potential publishing partners about 
forming an alliance similar to its link with dupont publishing 
inc she said playboy in 1988 acquired a 20 percent interest in 
the publisher of the dupont registry a monthly magazine for car 
buffs 
buzz zaino an industry analyst and managing director of trust 
co of the west in new york said the recapitalization will help 
playboy make similar deals 
it does provide her the flexibilty to expand the business with 
the use of stock either by selling stock in a public offering or 
using the stock to acquire other business he said 
