japan sought to assure world financial leaders 
monday that its stock and money markets are sound and it will 
continue efforts to cut its huge trade surplus 
there was no major movement of capital out of the stock and 
bond markets despite this uneasiness over sharp market declines 
earlier this year yasushi mieno governor of the bank of japan 
told the 22nation interim committee of the international monetary 
fund 
there has been no change in the basic soundness of japans 
fundamentals the central bank chief said in fact the markets 
are now considerably more stable than they were earlier this year 
the key index of the tokyo stock market plunged more than 25 
percent early this year as interest rates shot up and the yen lost 
roughly 10 percent of its value against the dollar 
the stock market has stabilized in recent weeks and the index 
has rebounded more than 10 percent from its low 
mieno also said he is confident that the current account 
surplus will continue to come steadily down provided the yen 
doesnt weaken further the yens decline has made japanese exports 
cheaper and imports more expensive 
the current account surplus should be reduced by a combination 
of strong growth in japans domestic demand and promotion of 
adjustments such as expanding overseas production by japanese 
firms he said 
but realizing that the yens depreciation may well put a 
damper on such promotion of adjustments i believe it is important 
for the exchange rate of the yen to be stabilized in such a way 
that better reflects japans economic fundamentals mieno said 
in effect advocating a stronger yen 
mieno told a news conference sunday he is not advocating a 
specific yendollar exchange rate but would prefer some 
strengthening of japans currency 
japans current account surplus fell from 797 billion in 1988 
to 572 billion last year or 2 percent of gross national product 
he said 
the world economic outlook is for continued firm growth 
mieno said still there will be a slight decline in the growth 
rate this year he predicted adding that the sweeping change in 
east europe and german unification have brought unprecedented 
uncertainties 
the sudden need for massive new investment in europe along with 
continued capital for the third world makes it imperative for 
industrial countries as a whole to increase their savings to 
prevent a global upsurge in interest rates and to support sustained 
global economic development mieno said 
he predicted japanese consumer prices would rise only 16 
percent this year with real economic growth of 4 percent and 
domestic demand up 46 percent 
