<TEXT>
consumer prices rose a record 863 percent on 
average in the third world last year spurred by a 350 percent rise 
in latin america the international monetary fund reported monday 
among 22 industrial countries prices rose 45 percent up from 
the 34 percent of 1988 the increases ranged from 11 percent in 
the netherlands to 208 percent in iceland japan had 23 percent 
and west germany 28 percent 
the united states the worlds largest economy was a little 
above the average at 48 percent 
the fund gets figures from its member countries but calculates 
on its own basis to make them comparable so rates for individual 
countries sometimes differ from those published by governments 
themselves 
latin american average prices were influenced heavily by runaway 
inflation in two of the areas most important countries argentina 
which had inflation of 3079 percent and brazil at 1287 percent 
the argentine figures meant the price of a basket of goods rose 30 
times during the course of the year 
peru had an even higher inflation rate of 3398 percent 
mexico which has adopted a strict austerity program saw its 
inflation rate drop to 20 percent from 114 percent in 1988 
the fund classifies 130 of its members as developing 
countries including those in eastern europe the soviet union 
does not belong and the fund gives no figures for it 
for its seven european members outside the industrial group the 
inflation rate rose in 1989 to an average 232 percent the average 
reflected yugoslavias 1239 percent inflation rate and polands 
rate of 244 percent 
a fund official said polands inflation rate has dropped sharply 
this year because of the new noncommunist governments shock 
program to shift away from central planning to a market system the 
program has abolished subsidies and cut back government spending 
annual figures for africa and the middle east were incomplete 
many middle east countries have not been reporting in recent years 
among those that have israels inflation rate rose to 202 percent 
last year from 163 percent in 1988 and egypts rose to 213 
percent from 177 percent 
africas average appeared steady 189 percent in 1988 and 212 
percent in the third quarter of 1989 the african average masked a 
wide range from zambias annual 186 percent rate last october to 
small price reductions in several countries including chad togo 
and the central african republic 
only asia showed a decline in the inflation rate for 21 
countries in that region the annual average inflation rate dropped 
to 102 percent last year from 118 percent in 1988 
chinas rate declined to 163 percent from 207 percent and 
indias also was falling from 94 percent in 1988 to an annual 
rate of 62 percent in the third quarter of 1989 
