<TEXT>
the bush administration on monday proposed 
changes in antitrust law that would relax restrictions on joint 
production ventures between us companies to produce new 
technologies 
the measure intended to enable us companies to better compete 
in the global marketplace would reduce the amount of damages that 
plaintiffs in antitrust suits could collect from companies involved 
in the joint ventures 
the legislation unveiled by attorney general dick thornburgh 
and commerce secretary robert mosbacher would also require courts 
to consider the effects of a joint venture on competition in 
foreign as well as domestic markets when determining if there is an 
antitrust violation 
antitrust restrictions on joint research and development 
ventures were relaxed by congress in 1984 the administration bill 
would extend the concept to joint production ventures 
the bill would help us firms face unprecedented worldwide 
challenges by bringing important research from the laboratory to 
the marketplace efficiently cost effectively and with less risk 
mosbacher said in a statement 
under the proposal plaintiffs could not collect treble damages 
from an antitrust judgment against companies that participate in a 
cooperative joint venture the bill would allow plaintiffs to 
collect only the money they lost as a result of the 
anticompetitive practice 
sen howard metzenbaum dohio chairman of the judiciary 
committees antitrust subcommittee said the proposal was 
unnecessary and could be harmful 
i say to the president show me which deals are being lost due 
to fears of antitrust suits metzenbaum said 
the real reason american companies are falling behiond is 
because they have been too busy trying to devour the competition 
with mergers lbos leveraged buyouts or management takeovers with 
borrowed money and hostile takeovers 
