northrop corp employees to proceed with portions of their lawsuit 
against the defense firm that the justice department declined to 
include when joining the suit 
us district judge david v kenyons ruling monday means former 
northrop manager david peterson and engineer jeff kroll can pursue 
claims that could net them as much as 60 million in damages said 
attorney phillip e benson 
its a novel issue and precedentsetting benson said 
peterson and kroll allege in their whistleblower suit that 
northrop committed more than 100 million in fraud in the 
production of the mx missile guidance systems 
the suit accuses the firm of falsifying tests and mischarging 
the government for tests and parts used in the inertial measurement 
units on the missile which are vital parts in the guidance systems 
the justice department announced last year it was picking up 
substantial portions of the suit northrop had sought to 
dismiss the claims that the government declined to join 
those remaining claims involved specific instances of alleged 
mischarging and test falsification 
but kenyon said monday the former employees will be permitted 
to pursue the claims which were not adopted by the government 
even though those claims will be dropped from the joint 
governmentemployee lawsuit 
kenyon said he would call another hearing to determine whether 
the severed claims could be included in a separate lawsuit 
northrop attorneys declined to comment 
in related rulings kenyon rejected northrops contention the 
employees lawsuit was unconstitutional but he agreed with the 
company that the government failed to be specific enough in 
alleging wrongdoing 
the judge gave the government 30 days to file a tighter version 
of the suit 
</TEXT>
