<TEXT>
a survey of 50 companies with pension plans 
underfunded by 40 million or more each shows those corporations 
together have a potential 14 billion shortfall the pension 
benefit guaranty corp said monday 
james lockhart director of the agency said the firms on the 
list were not necessarily in poor financial health he also said 
their inclusion did not mean they had failed to properly fund their 
pension plans 
guaranteed benefits earned by participants in the plans are 
still secure because the funds assets are growing and guaranteed 
by the federal agency lockhart said 
the agency released the list because employees should be aware 
of how their pension plans are funded said an agency spokeswoman 
the list of 50 companines came from a survey of information 
filed by about 7000 corporations with the securities and exchange 
commission the survey did not include a review of pension plans 
for banks utlities life insurance property and casualty firms or 
companies not required to file with the sec 
potential abuse within the nations 17 trillion pension system 
is a growing concern on capitol hill where both house and senate 
panels are looking into the matter 
labor secretary elizabeth dole has asked congress to approve 
funding for an additional 100 agents to police the pensions system 
here are the 50 companies listed monday and the size of their 
potential shortfall if the plans were to close and the pbgc had to 
guarantee benefits 
allegheny international inc 52 million allegheny ludlum 
corp 79 million american airlines 258 million american 
financial corp 47 million anchor glass container corp 66 
million armco inc 323 million asi holding corp 194 million 
